    "closed_at": null,
    "body": "Input: `/api/articles/:query` where `:query` matches regex `/.+_\\d+([-~(,(.+_)?)]\\d+)*/`\r\nOutput:\r\n```javascript\r\n{\r\n    'isSuccess': boolean,\r\n    'reason': string,\r\n    'articles': \r\n    [\r\n        {\r\n            \"law\": string, // name\r\n            \"articles\": \r\n            [\r\n                {\r\n                    \"number\": string, // article number such as 34-1\r\n                    \"content\": string\r\n                }\r\n            ]\r\n        }\r\n    ]\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\n\r\nThe square brackets in the input syntax are the main spirit. Here's an example for the input query: `\"公司法_4,民法_3,12~15-1\"`\r\n\r\nYou can think possibilities in the square brackets as binary operators with different meaning:\r\n* `\"-\"`: concatenate 2 positive integer to form an article number such as \"34-1\".\r\n* `\"~\"`: indicate successive articles such as the step 2 in #6. And I think using \"~\" would be better than using \"_\" for avoiding confusion, because therefore \"_\" is used only for representing the concatenation between law name and article number(s).\r\n* `\",\"`: indicate separate articles in the same regulation. For example \"3,7\" would mean article 3 and article 7.\r\n* `\",.+_\"`: concatenate another law and its article numbers.\r\n\r\nThis kind of query may cause massive data, so we may have to forbid users to call such an API. But anyway it could be a syntax to represent multiple articles from multiple regulations in a pure-text string."
  },
